# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
<overview>
<p>The Tatsumaki-class destroyer was the Draconis Combine's first domestically produced WarShip in centuries, commissioned in secret at Stellar Trek Enterprises' Terada Shipyards on Dieron beginning in 3058. Named for the Japanese word for "tornado," the design was intended to announce the Combine's return to interstellar naval power with a vessel that could match Clan capital ships in a close-range engagement. Conceived as a fleet escort and boarding platform, the Tatsumaki carried a dense weapons fit and a full battalion of battle armor troopers, giving fleet commanders an aggressive tool for convoy defense and ship-to-ship assault operations. The class earned a mixed reputation, however, with its fearsome armament offset by persistent reliability concerns that limited operational availability and strained the Combine's already thin pool of trained naval technicians.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>At 520,000 tons, the Tatsumaki is a compact destroyer built for close-range fleet escort and boarding operations. Naval autocannons form the backbone of its broadside armament, distributed across every arc except the direct stern to deliver punishing kinetic barrages at short range. A heavy naval gauss rifle in the nose supplements the forward battery, while naval PPCs at both capital and sub-capital scales provide sustained energy fire across multiple arcs. Massed LRM launchers fitted with Artemis IV fire control and conventional Gauss rifles add long-range precision, and layered pulse laser and anti-missile coverage protects against fighter strikes and incoming ordnance. Five hundred forty-four double heat sinks manage the considerable thermal demands of such a dense weapons fit.</p><p>Four hundred seventy-five tons of ferro-carbide armor provide excellent protection for the vessel's displacement, and a lithium-fusion battery enables rapid successive jumps, a significant tactical advantage for a destroyer tasked with escorting JumpShip convoys. Eighteen aerospace fighters, fifteen small craft, and a full battalion of 108 battle armor troops make the Tatsumaki an ideal boarding platform, capable of overwhelming hostile crews through sheer numbers. Two docking collars and two 200-meter gravity decks round out the design. The class achieves an impressive thrust profile for its mass, reaching three gravities at maximum acceleration.</p><p>These strengths are offset by serious reliability problems that plagued the design from commissioning. Turret mechanisms proved prone to jamming under sustained fire, and persistent coolant leaks in the KF Drive system defied repeated repair attempts. Each vessel required nearly double the standard complement of technical crew to remain combat-ready, an enormous logistical burden that limited the class's operational independence and contributed to the Combine Admiralty's decision to halt further construction.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The DCS Lair of Mighty Wyrms was the first Tatsumaki-class destroyer, commissioned around 3058 and initially stationed near the gas giant Gilgamesh in the Luthien system to avoid detection. The vessel sustained damage during Operation BULLDOG but was repaired with the assistance of Clan Nova Cat technicians. By 3067, it was the sole surviving example of its class. During the Jihad, the Lair of Mighty Wyrms served as a command vessel in Task Force CRONUS, contributing to the capture of the Titan Yards in 3078 before redeploying to New Samarkand in 3079 to defend the Combine's temporary capital. In 3100, during the Second Combine-Dominion War, the vessel participated in Coordinator Hohiro Kurita's strike against Rasalhague alongside the Winds of Heaven and Dieron Star. Though the Nightlord-class battleship CGB Ursa Major was finally destroyed in the engagement, the Lair of Mighty Wyrms suffered a catastrophic jump drive failure two jumps after escaping the battle and was scuttled by her crew in an uninhabited system.</p><p>The DCS Dragon's Last Tear was the second hull, completing construction in late 3058. In late 3062, Kokuryu-kai elements exploited discontent within the DCMS over Clan Ghost Bear's occupation of former Combine territory. The Dragon's Last Tear escorted the Alshain Avengers in an unauthorized assault on Alshain, the Ghost Bear capital world. The destroyer was easily destroyed by the Nightlord-class battleship CGB Ursa Major, and the surviving Avengers who reached the surface were wiped out by enraged Ghost Bear forces. The loss of Dragon's Last Tear and the attack on Alshain directly precipitated the First Dominion-Combine War.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Tatsumaki-class destroyer emerged from the Draconis Combine's ambitious effort to rebuild its naval capabilities during the late 3050s. The Clan invasions had exposed the Combine's near-total lack of WarShip assets, and the DCMS high command recognized that any future defensive strategy required capital vessels of its own. Stellar Trek Enterprises received the contract to construct the new class at its Terada Shipyards facility orbiting Dieron, with production conducted under strict secrecy to prevent foreign intelligence services from learning the program's scope.</p><p>The secrecy came at a cost. Terada Shipyards had limited experience with capital ship construction, and the compressed timeline left little room for proper testing or quality assurance. Chronic reliability problems plagued every hull that left the yard, requiring far more maintenance personnel than a destroyer of comparable displacement would normally demand. These difficulties strained the Combine's already thin pool of trained naval engineers and called the viability of the entire program into question.</p><p>Only two keels were laid down before the DCMS halted further procurement. The first vessel entered service around 3058 and was initially hidden in the outer reaches of the Luthien system. It participated in Operation BULLDOG against the Smoke Jaguars, sustaining damage that Clan Nova Cat technicians later helped repair. The second hull's career ended far more abruptly. In late 3062, rogue elements within the Kokuryu-kai secret society commandeered the vessel for an unauthorized assault on the Ghost Bear capital world. A Nightlord-class battleship destroyed it with ease, and the incident precipitated the First Dominion-Combine War.</p><p>With the class reduced to a single vessel and no prospect of further construction, the Combine Admiralty pressed its sole remaining Tatsumaki into continued service. The vessel contributed to several major Combine naval operations through the Jihad and into the early thirty-second century before the Second Combine-Dominion War brought the class to its end. During Coordinator Hohiro Kurita's strike against Rasalhague in 3100, the last Tatsumaki suffered a catastrophic jump drive failure after escaping the engagement and was scuttled by her crew in an uninhabited system. Both destroyers were thus ultimately lost in connection with the same Ghost Bear adversary, separated by nearly four decades.</p>
</history>

